were analyzed(CW ranging from 4.4 to 77.84 mm ). Among them, we identified 110 immature females (mean 24.57 ± 11.01 mm CW) and 264 mature females (49.09 ± 5.32 mm CW). For males, we found 93 (23.48 ± 11.71 mm CW) immature individuals and identified 144 (50.20± 10.13 mm CW)mature (gonadal and morphometric) individuals. The largest individuals captured measuring 71.64 and 77.84 mm CW for females and males, respectively. Our sample size was limited by low crab abundance, however, we used ecological parameters established by
